  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Devising practical approaches for mobilising investment capital and transfer of technology for Africa#s pharmaceutical industry</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Key to developing the pharmaceutical industry in Africa is that it can produce high quality affordable essential medicines and that the industry is sustainable. To make the transition from the status quo, where many companies operate well below international standards, to one where all remaining companies are at international standards requires that companies can access affordable long term capital, that they receive support during the transition phase in the form of time limited incentives and that they can access technology to improve quality standards and expand their product portfolios.
Whilst these requirements are well known, there is a lack of insights into how to effectively address them. Ensuring full alignment with, and building up on, UNIDO&#x2019;s ongoing global project to strengthen the local manufacturing of essential medicines in developing and least developed countries, this intervention&#x2019;s specific objective is to enable pharmaceutical companies in Africa to access finance and technology for upgrading production capacities to international standards. It will seek to do so through (i) producing and communicating a guidance document for policy-makers, financial actors (with a special focus on DFIs), development agents, and others, on improving access of African pharmaceutical manufacturers to investment capital (covering incentive packages, investment promotion and technology transfer, affordable finance); and through (ii) raising awareness of opportunities for partnerships between companies from Africa and Germany (Europe) at a dedicated investment/technology event.
The former will include the holding of an Expert Group Meeting (EGM) on UNIDO premises, the latter is foreseen to be staged in close cooperation with the anticipated new UNIDO ITPO in Bonn, expected to become operational in Q1/2017.</narrative>
  </description>
